{
  "Sperm are produced in the:": "",
  "Epididymis": "",
  "Seminiferous tubules of the testes": "",
  "Vas deferens": "",
  "Prostate gland": "",
  "Sperm production (spermatogenesis) occurs within the seminiferous tubules of the testes, where spermatogonia undergo meiosis and differentiation with the support of Sertoli cells to eventually form mature spermatozoa.": "",
  "Leydig (interstitial) cells produce which hormone?": "",
  "FSH in response to GnRH pulsatile stimulation": "",
  "Inhibin as a negative feedback hormone to the pituitary": "",
  "Testosterone in response to LH stimulation": "",
  "Estrogen via aromatase conversion in peripheral tissues": "",
  "Leydig cells (also called interstitial cells) are located between the seminiferous tubules and produce testosterone in response to luteinizing hormone (LH) from the anterior pituitary, serving as the primary endocrine function of the testes.": "",
  "The scrotum maintains the testes at a temperature that is:": "",
  "Higher than core body temperature": "",
  "The same as core body temperature": "",
  "Slightly lower than core body temperature (about 2-3 degrees C below)": "",
  "Much colder, about 10 degrees C below body temperature": "",
  "The scrotum keeps the testes approximately 2-3 degrees Celsius below core body temperature, which is essential for normal spermatogenesis. The cremaster and dartos muscles adjust the position of the testes relative to the body to regulate this temperature.": "",
  "Spermatogenesis from spermatogonium to mature sperm takes approximately:": "",
  "74 days (about 2.5 months)": "",
  "7 days (approximately one week from start to finish)": "",
  "1 month (approximately 30 days from start to finish)": "",
  "1 year (approximately 365 days from start to finish)": "",
  "The complete process of spermatogenesis takes approximately 74 days (about 2.5 months) from the initial spermatogonium to a mature spermatozoon. This is a continuous process that begins at puberty and continues throughout a man's life.": "",
  "Sperm mature and are stored in the:": "",
  "Seminiferous tubules": "",
  "Seminal vesicles": "",
  "After leaving the seminiferous tubules, immature sperm travel to the epididymis where they undergo a maturation process lasting about 12 days, gaining the ability to swim and fertilize an egg. The epididymis also serves as the primary storage site for mature sperm.": "",
  "The seminal vesicles contribute approximately what percentage of semen volume?": "",
  "90-95%": "",
  "Less than 5%": "",
  "60-70%": "",
  "10-20%": "",
  "The seminal vesicles produce approximately 60-70% of the total semen volume, secreting a viscous, alkaline fluid rich in fructose (which provides energy for sperm), prostaglandins, and clotting proteins that support sperm viability and function.": "",
  "FSH acts on which cells in the male reproductive system?": "",
  "Prostate cells to produce alkaline fluid": "",
  "Leydig cells to produce testosterone": "",
  "Epididymal cells for sperm maturation": "",
  "Sertoli cells to support spermatogenesis": "",
  "Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) specifically targets Sertoli cells in the seminiferous tubules, stimulating them to produce androgen-binding protein and other factors that support and nourish developing sperm throughout spermatogenesis.": "",
  "The vas deferens connects the:": "",
  "Testis to the scrotum": "",
  "Bladder to the urethra": "",
  "Kidney to the bladder": "",
  "Epididymis to the ejaculatory duct": "",
  "The vas deferens (ductus deferens) is a muscular tube that transports mature sperm from the epididymis through the inguinal canal and around the bladder to the ejaculatory duct, where it merges with the duct of the seminal vesicle.": "",
  "The prostate gland secretes:": "",
  "Testosterone that promotes secondary sex characteristics and spermatogenesis": "",
  "A slightly alkaline fluid containing enzymes that helps neutralize vaginal acidity": "",
  "Sperm cells produced through spermatogenesis in the seminiferous tubules": "",
  "Fructose-rich fluid produced by the seminal vesicles that provides energy for sperm motility": "",
  "The prostate gland produces a thin, milky, slightly alkaline fluid that contributes about 25-30% of semen volume. This fluid contains enzymes like PSA (prostate-specific antigen) and citric acid, and its alkaline nature helps neutralize the acidic vaginal environment to protect sperm.": "",
  "During spermatogenesis, meiosis produces:": "",
  "Haploid (n) spermatids from diploid (2n) spermatogonia": "",
  "Tetraploid (4n) cells with doubled chromosomes": "",
  "Cells with no chromosomes": "",
  "Diploid (2n) cells identical to the parent cell": "",
  "Meiosis during spermatogenesis reduces the chromosome number from diploid (2n = 46 chromosomes) in spermatogonia to haploid (n = 23 chromosomes) in spermatids, which then undergo spermiogenesis to become mature spermatozoa ready for fertilization.": "",
  "What is spermatogenesis?": "",
  "The hormonal regulation of the testes by the pituitary gland": "",
  "The process of sperm production from spermatogonia through meiosis and differentiation in the seminiferous tubules": "",
  "The process of sperm transport through the vas deferens": "",
  "The release of mature sperm during ejaculation": "",
  "Spermatogenesis is the complete process of sperm cell development, beginning with diploid spermatogonia that undergo mitosis and then meiosis within the seminiferous tubules to produce haploid spermatids, which are subsequently remodeled into mature spermatozoa through spermiogenesis.": "",
  "What are Sertoli cells?": "",
  "Hormone-producing cells located between the seminiferous tubules": "",
  "Supportive 'nurse cells' within the seminiferous tubules that nourish, protect, and guide developing sperm": "",
  "Smooth muscle cells that line the epididymis": "",
  "Secretory cells of the prostate gland": "",
  "Sertoli cells (also called sustentacular or nurse cells) are columnar cells within the seminiferous tubules that support, nourish, and protect developing sperm. They form the blood-testis barrier, secrete fluid and androgen-binding protein, and produce inhibin to regulate FSH secretion.": "",
  "What is the blood-testis barrier?": "",
  "A barrier formed by tight junctions between Sertoli cells that isolates developing sperm from the immune system": "",
  "A layer of connective tissue that encapsulates each testis": "",
  "A physical wall between the testes and the abdominal cavity": "",
  "The scrotal skin that protects the testes from external pathogens": "",
  "The blood-testis barrier is formed by tight junctions between adjacent Sertoli cells, creating an immunologically privileged environment that prevents immune cells from contacting and attacking developing sperm, which express unique surface antigens not recognized as 'self' by the immune system.": "",
  "What is a vasectomy?": "",
  "A procedure that blocks the urethra to prevent urination": "",
  "Surgical removal of the prostate gland": "",
  "Surgical removal of the testes": "",
  "A surgical procedure that cuts and seals the vas deferens to prevent sperm from reaching the ejaculate": "",
  "A vasectomy is a male sterilization procedure in which the vas deferens on each side is surgically cut, tied, or sealed to prevent sperm from entering the ejaculate. Testosterone production and ejaculation still occur, but the semen contains no sperm.": "",
  "What is benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH)?": "",
  "A malignant cancer of the prostate gland": "",
  "A congenital absence of the prostate gland": "",
  "An infection of the prostate caused by bacteria": "",
  "Non-cancerous enlargement of the prostate gland common in older men that can compress the urethra and cause urinary obstruction": "",
  "Benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) is a non-cancerous enlargement of the prostate gland that commonly occurs in men over age 50. As the prostate grows, it compresses the prostatic urethra, causing symptoms like urinary hesitancy, weak stream, frequency, and nocturia.": "",
  "What does the term cryptorchidism mean?": "",
  "A condition where both testes are removed surgically": "",
  "A twisting of the spermatic cord causing ischemia": "",
  "An undescended testis that has failed to migrate from the abdomen into the scrotum": "",
  "An infection of the seminiferous tubules": "",
  "Cryptorchidism (from the Greek for 'hidden testis') is a condition in which one or both testes fail to descend from the abdominal cavity into the scrotum during fetal development. If untreated, it impairs spermatogenesis due to elevated temperature and increases the risk of testicular cancer.": "",
  "What is inhibin?": "",
  "A hormone produced by Sertoli cells that selectively inhibits FSH secretion through negative feedback": "",
  "A chemical in seminal fluid that activates sperm motility": "",
  "A hypothalamic hormone that triggers puberty": "",
  "A pituitary hormone that stimulates testosterone production": "",
  "Inhibin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by Sertoli cells in males (and granulosa cells in females) that provides selective negative feedback to the anterior pituitary gland, specifically inhibiting FSH secretion to help regulate the rate of spermatogenesis.": "",
  "What does the PSA (prostate-specific antigen) test measure?": "",
  "The level of FSH in the blood": "",
  "The number of sperm in a semen sample": "",
  "A protein produced by prostate cells that may be elevated in prostate cancer, BPH, or prostatitis": "",
  "Testosterone levels in the blood": "",
  "The PSA test measures the blood level of prostate-specific antigen, a protein produced by both normal and malignant prostate cells. Elevated PSA levels may indicate prostate cancer, but they can also be raised by benign conditions like BPH or prostatitis, so further evaluation is needed.": "",
  "What is the ejaculatory duct?": "",
  "The tube connecting the epididymis to the abdominal cavity": "",
  "A muscular sphincter that controls urine release": "",
  "A short duct formed by the union of the vas deferens and the seminal vesicle duct that passes through the prostate to the urethra": "",
  "The opening of the urethra at the tip of the penis": "",
  "The ejaculatory duct is a short paired duct formed by the junction of the vas deferens and the duct of the seminal vesicle. It passes through the prostate gland and opens into the prostatic urethra, delivering both sperm and seminal vesicle secretions during ejaculation.": "",
  "What does testosterone do in the male body?": "",
  "Only regulates the prostate gland": "",
  "Only promotes bone growth during puberty": "",
  "Drives secondary sex characteristics, spermatogenesis, libido, and muscle and bone development": "",
  "Only stimulates sperm production in the testes": "",
  "Testosterone is the primary male androgen with wide-ranging effects including driving secondary sex characteristics (facial hair, deep voice, body hair), stimulating spermatogenesis, promoting muscle mass and bone density, maintaining libido, and influencing mood and cognitive function.": "",
  "A 14-year-old boy is being evaluated because he has not yet shown signs of puberty. Blood tests reveal very low testosterone, LH, and FSH levels. His physician suspects a problem with the hypothalamic-pituitary axis. Which hormone is the hypothalamus likely failing to produce adequately?": "",
  "GnRH (gonadotropin-releasing hormone)": "",
  "Inhibin": "",
  "Testosterone": "",
  "ADH (antidiuretic hormone)": "",
  "GnRH from the hypothalamus is the initiating signal for the HPG axis, stimulating the anterior pituitary to release FSH and LH. Low levels of all three hormones (testosterone, LH, and FSH) indicate the problem is upstream at the hypothalamus, where inadequate GnRH pulsatile secretion fails to activate the reproductive cascade.": "",
  "A couple has been trying to conceive for 18 months without success. A semen analysis reveals a sperm count of 8 million per mL (normal is > 15 million/mL) with poor motility. Which of the following conditions could explain these findings?": "",
  "A varicocele (dilated veins in the scrotum) raising testicular temperature above optimal range": "",
  "Benign prostatic hyperplasia compressing the urethra": "",
  "An overactive anterior pituitary producing too much FSH": "",
  "Excess production of seminal vesicle fluid": "",
  "A varicocele is an enlargement of the pampiniform venous plexus within the scrotum that raises testicular temperature above the optimal range for spermatogenesis. This elevated temperature impairs sperm production and quality, resulting in oligospermia (low sperm count) and reduced motility, making it one of the most common treatable causes of male infertility.": "",
  "A 68-year-old man visits his doctor complaining of difficulty starting urination, a weak stream, and waking up multiple times at night to urinate. A digital rectal exam reveals a symmetrically enlarged, smooth, firm prostate. What is the most likely diagnosis?": "",
  "Kidney stones blocking the ureter": "",
  "Prostate cancer, which typically presents as an irregular, hard nodule": "",
  "Benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) causing compression of the prostatic urethra": "",
  "Urinary tract infection affecting the bladder": "",
  "The combination of obstructive urinary symptoms (hesitancy, weak stream, nocturia) with a symmetrically enlarged, smooth prostate on digital rectal exam is classic for BPH. In contrast, prostate cancer typically presents as an irregular, hard nodule, though the two conditions can coexist.": "",
  "A 16-year-old male athlete presents to the ER with sudden onset of severe left testicular pain and swelling that started during a soccer game. The affected testis appears higher in the scrotum and is extremely tender. What is the most likely diagnosis, and why is urgent treatment critical?": "",
  "Epididymitis; antibiotics should be started within 48 hours": "",
  "Cryptorchidism that suddenly became symptomatic": "",
  "A direct inguinal hernia requiring scheduled surgical repair": "",
  "Testicular torsion; the spermatic cord has twisted, cutting off blood supply, and surgical correction must occur within 6 hours to save the testis": "",
  "Testicular torsion is a surgical emergency in which the spermatic cord twists, cutting off the arterial blood supply to the testis. The classic presentation is sudden, severe testicular pain with a high-riding testis in a young male. Surgical detorsion must be performed within approximately 6 hours to prevent irreversible ischemic damage and testicular loss.": "",
  "A bodybuilder who has been using anabolic steroids (synthetic testosterone) for several years seeks medical help for infertility. His lab results show very low FSH, very low LH, and a near-zero sperm count. Why has exogenous testosterone caused infertility?": "",
  "High exogenous testosterone suppresses GnRH, FSH, and LH through negative feedback, shutting down spermatogenesis": "",
  "Anabolic steroids cause the testes to physically atrophy and disappear": "",
  "Exogenous testosterone blocks the seminal vesicles from producing fructose": "",
  "Exogenous testosterone directly destroys existing sperm in the epididymis": "",
  "Exogenous testosterone provides strong negative feedback to the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary, suppressing GnRH, FSH, and LH secretion. Without FSH to stimulate Sertoli cells and without intratesticular testosterone (which requires LH stimulation of Leydig cells), spermatogenesis ceases, leading to azoospermia and infertility.": "",
  "A newborn male is examined and the pediatrician notes that the right testis cannot be palpated in the scrotum. Ultrasound confirms it is located in the inguinal canal. The parents are counseled about the need for treatment. What is the primary concern if this condition is left untreated?": "",
  "The child will develop premature puberty": "",
  "The inguinal canal will become permanently blocked": "",
  "Increased risk of testicular cancer and impaired spermatogenesis due to elevated temperature": "",
  "The child will develop a urinary tract infection": "",
  "Cryptorchidism (undescended testis) left untreated increases the risk of testicular cancer by 5-10 times and causes impaired spermatogenesis because the inguinal canal temperature is too high for normal sperm development. Orchiopexy (surgical relocation of the testis to the scrotum) is typically performed by age 1 to reduce these risks.": "",
  "A 55-year-old man has his annual physical and a PSA blood test returns at 8.2 ng/mL (normal < 4.0). His physician recommends further evaluation. Why can't an elevated PSA alone confirm prostate cancer?": "",
  "PSA can be elevated by non-cancerous conditions such as BPH, prostatitis, or recent prostate manipulation, so a biopsy is needed for definitive diagnosis": "",
  "PSA is only produced by cancerous prostate cells, not normal ones": "",
  "PSA measures testosterone levels, not prostate health": "",
  "PSA is always elevated in men over 50 regardless of prostate health": "",
  "PSA (prostate-specific antigen) is produced by all prostate cells, not just cancerous ones. It can be elevated by BPH, prostatitis, urinary retention, or recent prostate procedures, which is why an elevated PSA is a screening tool, not a diagnostic test, and a tissue biopsy is required to confirm or rule out prostate cancer.": "",
  "A man who underwent a vasectomy two years ago asks his doctor whether the procedure has affected his testosterone levels or sexual function. What is the most accurate response?": "",
  "The testes gradually atrophy and stop producing sperm entirely": "",
  "Ejaculation no longer occurs after a vasectomy": "",
  "Testosterone levels and sexual function remain normal because the procedure only blocks sperm transport and does not affect Leydig cell hormone production": "",
  "Testosterone levels drop significantly because the testes can no longer function": "",
  "A vasectomy only cuts the vas deferens to prevent sperm from reaching the ejaculate. Leydig cells continue producing testosterone normally (since their blood supply is unaffected), and ejaculation still occurs because seminal vesicle and prostate secretions make up the majority of semen volume. Only the sperm component is absent.": "",
  "A 45-year-old man reports decreased libido, fatigue, loss of muscle mass, and depressed mood. Blood work reveals a total testosterone level of 180 ng/dL (normal: 300-1000). His LH and FSH are also low. What type of hypogonadism does this pattern suggest?": "",
  "Primary hypogonadism with the problem originating in the testes": "",
  "Secondary (central) hypogonadism with the problem originating in the hypothalamus or pituitary": "",
  "Normal age-related testosterone decline requiring no treatment": "",
  "Androgen insensitivity syndrome": "",
  "Low testosterone combined with low LH and FSH indicates secondary (central) hypogonadism, meaning the hypothalamus or pituitary is not adequately stimulating the testes. In primary hypogonadism, the testes are the problem and LH/FSH would be elevated (trying to stimulate the failing testes). This distinction is critical for determining the appropriate treatment approach.": "",
  "A medical student is studying erectile physiology and learns that erection involves vascular changes in the penis. A patient with long-standing diabetes and peripheral vascular disease reports progressive erectile dysfunction. What is the most likely underlying mechanism?": "",
  "Vascular damage from diabetes impairs blood flow to the erectile tissue, preventing adequate engorgement": "",
  "Excessive testosterone production overstimulating the erectile tissue": "",
  "The patient's prostate gland has become enlarged and is compressing the penile nerves": "",
  "The epididymis has become blocked, preventing normal ejaculation": "",
  "Erectile dysfunction in diabetic patients is commonly caused by vascular disease (damage to the endothelium of penile arteries) and diabetic neuropathy (damage to the parasympathetic nerves that mediate erection). Diabetes accelerates atherosclerosis and impairs nitric oxide-mediated vasodilation, reducing blood flow to the corpora cavernosa needed for erection.": ""
}